## Report: Answers to Coursework Questions

### Part 1.1 - JAX-RS Resource Lifecycle and In-Memory Data Management

By default, JAX-RS creates a new instance of each Resource class for 
every incoming HTTP request (request-scoped lifecycle). This means any 
instance variables declared inside a resource class are initialised 
fresh for every request and are not shared between requests.

This has a direct implication for in-memory data storage: if data were 
stored as instance variables on the resource class, it would be lost 
the moment a request completes. To solve this, all persistent data in 
this project is stored in a singleton DataStore class using 
ConcurrentHashMap, which is a thread-safe implementation of HashMap 
from java.util.concurrent. Because ConcurrentHashMap allows multiple 
threads to read and perform localised writes simultaneously without 
requiring full synchronisation locks, it prevents race conditions where 
two concurrent requests could corrupt shared data. The singleton ensures 
that every request-scoped resource instance accesses the same shared 
data structure, achieving data persistence across the lifetime of the 
running server.

---

### Part 1.2 - HATEOAS and Hypermedia in RESTful Design

HATEOAS (Hypermedia As The Engine Of Application State) is considered 
a hallmark of mature RESTful design because it makes the API 
self-descriptive and discoverable. Instead of a client needing to know 
every URL in advance from static documentation, each API response 
includes embedded links that tell the client what actions are available 
and where to find related resources.

For client developers, this offers two major advantages. First, it 
dramatically reduces coupling — if the server changes a URL, clients 
following the hypermedia links adapt automatically rather than breaking. 
Second, it lowers the onboarding barrier: a developer can explore the 
entire API by starting at a single root endpoint and following the links 
provided, much like browsing a website. In contrast, static 
documentation becomes stale the moment the API evolves, creating a 
maintenance burden and a source of bugs.

---

### Part 2.1 - Returning IDs vs Full Objects in List Responses

When a GET /rooms endpoint returns only a list of IDs, the client must 
make a separate GET /rooms/{id} request for each room it wants full 
details on. This is known as the N+1 problem. For a campus with hundreds 
of rooms, this generates excessive network round-trips, increasing 
latency and server load.

Returning full room objects in the list response trades a larger initial 
payload for far fewer HTTP requests. For consumers such as facility 
management dashboards or building automation systems that need to process 
all room data at once, this is clearly superior. The trade-off is only 
relevant when clients routinely need just a subset of the data, in which 
case pagination or sparse fieldsets would be better solutions.

---

### Part 2.2 - Is DELETE Idempotent in This Implementation?

RFC 7231 defines an idempotent operation as one where making the same 
request multiple times produces the same server-side state. Under that 
definition, DELETE is considered idempotent because after the first 
call the room is gone, and after the second call the room is still gone. 
The server state is identical.

However, in this implementation the HTTP response code differs: the 
first DELETE returns 200 OK, while any subsequent DELETE on the same ID 
returns 404 Not Found since the room no longer exists. This is a 
pragmatic and widely accepted approach. The idempotency guarantee 
relates to server state, not to response codes. A 404 on repeated 
deletion is not a failure — it accurately reflects reality. No data 
corruption or inconsistency is introduced by sending the same DELETE 
request multiple times.

---

### Part 3.1 - Consequences of @Consumes Media Type Mismatch

The @Consumes(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON) annotation declares that the 
endpoint only accepts request bodies formatted as application/json. If 
a client sends a request with a Content-Type of text/plain or 
application/xml, JAX-RS automatically returns an HTTP 415 Unsupported 
Media Type response without ever invoking the resource method. This is 
handled entirely by the JAX-RS runtime content negotiation mechanism. 
The benefit is that malformed or incompatible payloads are rejected at 
the framework layer before any business logic executes, acting as a 
first line of input validation.

---

### Part 3.2 - @QueryParam vs Path Segment for Filtering

Using @QueryParam for filtering (e.g. GET /sensors?type=CO2) is the 
correct RESTful pattern for several reasons. Query parameters are 
semantically optional — their absence returns the full unfiltered 
collection, which is natural. They clearly communicate that we are 
refining a search over a collection rather than identifying a specific 
resource.

In contrast, embedding the filter in the path (/sensors/type/CO2) 
implies that type/CO2 is part of the resource identity — a specific 
uniquely addressable thing. This is semantically misleading. It also 
makes combining multiple filters awkward, whereas query parameters 
compose naturally: ?type=CO2&status=ACTIVE. Additionally, 
query-parameter-based filtering plays well with caching infrastructure 
which treats the path as the primary cache key.

---

### Part 4.1 - Benefits of the Sub-Resource Locator Pattern

The Sub-Resource Locator pattern allows JAX-RS to delegate handling of 
nested paths to dedicated classes. In this project, SensorResource 
handles /sensors and /sensors/{sensorId}, while SensorReadingResource 
exclusively handles the /readings sub-path.

The architectural benefits are significant. Each class has a single 
focused responsibility (Single Responsibility Principle), making it 
easier to test, maintain, and extend independently. Contrast this with 
the alternative: one enormous resource class handling every possible 
path. As the API grows, such a monolithic controller becomes 
unmanageable and harder to read. Delegation to sub-resources naturally 
mirrors the hierarchical structure of the domain where a reading belongs 
to a sensor, making the code architecture self-documenting.

---

### Part 5.2 - Why HTTP 422 Is More Semantically Accurate Than 404

HTTP 404 Not Found communicates that the requested URL endpoint does 
not exist on the server. When a client POSTs to /api/v1/sensors, that 
URL is perfectly valid and the endpoint exists — so a 404 would be 
factually incorrect and confusing.

The real problem is that the JSON payload contains a roomId value that 
references a room which does not exist in the system — a semantic 
validation failure rather than a routing failure. HTTP 422 Unprocessable 
Entity was designed precisely for this scenario: the request was 
syntactically valid but the server cannot process it because of a 
logical inconsistency in the payload content. This gives client 
developers a much clearer signal that the request structure is fine but 
the data inside it references something that does not exist.

---

### Part 5.3 - Why HTTP 403 Forbidden for a MAINTENANCE Sensor

HTTP 403 Forbidden is used here because the client request is 
understood and valid — the sensor exists and the URL is correct — but 
the server is refusing to process it due to the current state of the 
resource. A sensor in MAINTENANCE status has been deliberately taken 
offline by an administrator, meaning it is physically disconnected and 
cannot accept new readings.

The 403 status communicates that this is a refusal based on business 
rules and resource state, not a client error in forming the request. 
Using 404 would be wrong because the sensor exists in the system. Using 
400 would be wrong because the request body is valid JSON. HTTP 403 
accurately signals that the server understands the request but is 
refusing it based on the current state of the resource.

---

### Part 5.4 - Security Risks of Exposing Stack Traces

Exposing raw Java stack traces in API error responses is a serious 
security vulnerability for several reasons.

First, library and version fingerprinting: stack traces include 
fully-qualified class names such as org.glassfish.jersey.server or 
com.fasterxml.jackson.databind. Attackers use these to identify exact 
library versions and cross-reference them against public CVE databases 
to find known exploits.

Second, internal architecture disclosure: package names and class 
hierarchies reveal the application internal structure, design patterns, 
and technology choices that should remain private.

Third, file path exposure: stack frames often include absolute file 
paths on the server which reveals the directory layout and can assist 
path traversal attacks.

Fourth, logic flow revelation: the sequence of method calls in a trace 
can expose business logic, helping attackers craft inputs designed to 
trigger vulnerable code paths.

The GlobalExceptionMapper solves this by catching all uncaught 
exceptions, logging the full detail server-side only, and returning a 
sanitised generic message to the client.

---

### Part 5.5 - Why JAX-RS Filters Are Superior to Inline Logging

Inserting Logger.info() statements manually inside every resource method 
has significant drawbacks. It violates the DRY principle (Do not Repeat 
Yourself) as the same boilerplate appears across dozens of methods. It 
is easy to forget — a newly added endpoint might go unlogged. It 
pollutes resource classes with infrastructure concerns making them 
harder to read.

JAX-RS Filters address all of these issues by implementing logging as a 
cross-cutting concern at the framework level. The LoggingFilter class 
intercepts every request and response automatically regardless of which 
resource handles them. This guarantees consistent complete coverage with 
no risk of omission. It also means the format and behaviour of logging 
can be changed in a single class rather than hunting through every 
resource method. This separation of concerns is a foundational principle 
of professional maintainable API design.
